🔐 What is an Identity Provider (IdP)?

An Identity Provider (IdP) is a system that:

Authenticates users (checks username/password, MFA, etc.)

Issues authentication proof (like a SAML assertion)

Tells other applications:
👉 “This user is verified. You can trust them.”

🏢 In Your Project Context

Your Rails app = Service Provider (SP)
ADFS / Okta / Azure AD = Identity Provider (IdP)

The IdP handles login.
Your Rails app trusts the IdP.

🧩 What Are These Systems?
1️⃣ Active Directory Federation Services (ADFS)

Microsoft product

Used mostly by enterprises

Connected to Active Directory

Common in internal corporate environments

👉 Companies using Windows + AD often use ADFS.

2️⃣ Okta

Cloud-based identity provider

Popular SaaS identity platform

Supports SAML, OAuth, OpenID Connect

Very common for modern startups & SaaS apps

3️⃣ Microsoft Azure Active Directory (Azure AD)

Cloud-based identity service by Microsoft

Now called Microsoft Entra ID

Used for Office 365, enterprise apps

Supports SAML, OAuth, OpenID Connect

🧠 Simple Analogy

Think of it like this:

Your Rails app = Hotel

IdP (ADFS/Okta/Azure AD) = Passport office

User = Traveler

The hotel doesn’t verify passport itself.

Instead:

Hotel redirects traveler to passport office.

Passport office verifies identity.

Passport office sends stamped document.

Hotel trusts it and gives room.

🔁 Technical Flow in Simple Terms

User opens Rails app

Rails redirects to IdP

IdP authenticates user

IdP sends SAML response

Rails verifies signature

User logged in

🎯 Interview Answer Version

If interviewer asks:

“What is an Identity Provider?”

You say:

An Identity Provider is a trusted system responsible for authenticating users and issuing identity assertions using protocols like SAML. In enterprise environments, this is commonly ADFS, Azure AD, or Okta. Our Rails application acts as the Service Provider and delegates authentication to the IdP.

🔥 Clean. Senior. Confident.